Autonomic nervous system and organization

[!INFO]
The parasympathetic outflow is from CN 3,7,9,10.
The nerves other than 10 provide parasympathetic plexuses within the skull.
PNS and SNS both have actylcholine secreted by the preganglionic neuron. Both have nicotinic receptors on the post ganglionic neurons.
However, in the the SNS post ganglionic neurons secretes epinephrine or norepinephrine.
In the PNS, the post ganglionic neurons secretes acetylcholine which binds to muscarinic receptors on the effector organ.

Vagus nerve anatomy

#2020BSQ-JUL/Q55

Dorsal nucleus of the vagus nerve is a mixed visceral afferent and efferent nucleus.
It supplies the gut upto the distal transverse colong (midgut / hindgut junction)
Nucleus ambiguus -> supplies efferent fibers to striated muscle of the pharynx and larynx.

Passes through the jugular foramen.
Lies in the posterior carotid sheath.
Superior laryngeal branch supplies larynx above the vocal folds.
Recurrent laryngeal nerve is given off the right vagus nerve.

The vagi enter the abdomen through the oesophageal opening of the diaphragm.

In unilateral paralysis of the vagal nerve, the uvula deviates to the normal side.

Glossopharyngeal nerve lesions

Complete section of the glossopharyngeal nerve results in

  1. sensory loss in the pharynx, ?absent gag reflex
  2. loss of taste and common sensation over the posterior one-third of the tongue,
  3. some pharyngeal weakness and
  4. loss of salivation from the parotid gland

Anatomy of the spinal cord

In adults, the cord terminates at the level of L1-L2. Thus the cord spans within 20 bony vertebrae. In a child, it terminates at the upper border of L3.

[!INFO] Levels
Each intervertebral foramina contains the numerically corresponding spinal nerve. However, the spinal segment directly behind a particular vertebral body is about 1(upper thoracic) or 2 (lower thoracic) segments lowers.

Cauda equina syndrome

The cauda equina is made up of the ascending and descending nerve roots from L2 to the coccygeal segments. It is responsible for lower limb movement and sensation, bladder control/urination, external anal sphincter control and defecation, sexual function, and sensation of the genitalia and perineal region. Commonest cause is disk prolapse. Source

The parietal lobe integrates sensory information into a 'perception' within 3D space.
i.e Seeing pans, pots and a cooker is perceived as a 'kitchen' and your orientation with respect to it.
The parietal love is also required for learning and carrying out complex movements.

Parietal love dysfunction results in :

  1. Agraphia - inability to write

  2. acalculia - inability to do math

  3. alexia - inability to read

  4. Left right agnosis (inability to tell left from right)

  5. Finger agnosis (inability to identify fingers separately)

  6. Astereognosis - inability to identify and object by touch

  7. Occulomotor apraxia - loss of voluntary control of gaze

  8. simultagnosis (inability to identify things in context - i.e can see trees but can't recognise forrest)

  9. Optic apraxia - reaching for something and missing while looking at it.

"Sample variance" here actually means "estimate of the population variance" based on the variance of the sample that we have. Hence, the sum of differences is divided by n-1 and not n. (where n = sample size).

Randomization in clinical trials

#2020BSQ-JUL/Q58

The aim is to minimize variation in sample size and variation in baseline characteristics (covariates) between treatment and control groups.

Randomization:

Randomization is the process of assigning participants to treatment and control groups, assuming that each participant has an equal chance of being assigned to any group

Randomization can use a method as simple as a coin toss but better methods are available.

Benefits of randomization:

  1. Eliminate influence of covariates on the dependent variable when comparing control and treatment groups.
  2. Eliminates selection bias (i.e eliminates the change of individuals having unequal chances of being assigned to the study groups)
  3. ANCOVA and multivariate ANCOVA are techniques used to adjust for covariate imbalance between the groups during the analysis stage.

Techniques of randomization

  1. Simple randomization : complete randomness => flipping a coin.
    1. Good for large trials but will produce uneven groups in small trials (n< 100)
  2. Block randomization
    1. Ensures equal sample sizes between groups
    2. but may introduce unevenness in covariates.
    3. Makes groups comparable within known confounding factors.
  3. Stratified randomization
    1. Achieves balance among covariate characteristics between groups.
  4. Adaptive covariate randomization
    1. "covariate adaptive randomization method allows for the examination of previous participant group assignments to make a case-by-case decision on group assignment for each individual who enrolls in the study"

[!INFO] Blinding
In a single blind study - particicipants are blinded.

  • Minimizes performace bias (i.e subjects will perform differently when they have knowledge of their treatment / control group)
    In a double blind study - participants and researchers are blinded.
  • double blinding also minimizes assessment bias (when researches assess a participants different when they have knowledge about whether subject belongs to the the control / treatment group)

Types of error

- Type 1 error (where the null hypothesis is incorrectly rejected)
- Type 2 error (where thenull hypothesis is incorrectly accepted)

Level of evidence

Systematic revies of RCTs provide level 1 evidence.
Level 2: RCT
Level 3:
Other levels are confusing.

Covariates (to understand randomization)

Covariates are any variable that is statistically related to the dependent variable in a study. (i.e changing a covariate will affect the dependent variable in question).
Covaraites can be

  1. The independent variable being studies
  2. Confounding variables.
    Covariates are continuous variables. So as opposed to measuring the effect of 'treatment or no treatment' on a dependent variable, using covariates allows us to to check the effect of a continuous variable on the dependent variable.
  • Linear regression is one method of analysing the effect of a covariate on the dependent variable; it's used when the dependent variable is also continuous.

if the covariate accounts for a reasonable amount variation in the dependent variable, we increase statistical power to examine effects of a factor that interests us; again, this provides clear benefits. Conversely, including a covariate that does not explain reasonable variation in the dependent variable decreases power to examine effects of a factor. Source
